{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491252","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491252"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:39:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:39:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"891"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"891","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/891"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.04,0.2,0.57,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"891"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100694"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"891","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/891"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"891"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83116"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"568"},{"type":"tags","id":"1216"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"6215"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"990"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1047"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28478"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100694","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/100694"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of a painful and swollen right index finger. She pricked her finger on a rose thorn whilst gardening and initially thought nothing of it. However, over the last two days, the finger has become increasingly painful and swollen. She has a medical history of atrial fibrillation for which she takes apixaban. She does not have any other significant medical history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The right index finger is diffusely swollen and held slightly flexed at rest. There is marked tenderness along the flexor aspect of her finger, and any attempted passive extension is limited by severe pain.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cellulitis","Subcutaneous abscess","Flexor tendon sheath haematoma","Flexor tenosynovitis","Felon"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic features of pyogenic \u003Cstrong\u003Eflexor tenosynovitis\u003C/strong\u003E, an infection of the flexor tendon sheath that requires urgent treatment. The diagnosis is based on Kanavel\u0027s four cardinal signs, all of which are present in this case: fusiform (uniform, sausage-like) swelling of the digit, the finger held in partial flexion at rest, tenderness along the course of the tendon sheath, and severe pain on passive extension of the finger.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECellulitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with diffuse erythema, warmth, and swelling of the skin and subcutaneous tissues, but would not specifically cause the finger to be held in flexion or demonstrate pain specifically along the tendon sheath. While cellulitis may coexist with tenosynovitis, the specific tendon-related findings point to involvement of deeper structures.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Esubcutaneous abscess\u003C/strong\u003E would present as a localized collection of pus with surrounding erythema and fluctuance. It would not typically cause tenderness along the entire length of the tendon sheath or the characteristic flexed posture seen in tenosynovitis. An abscess would be more focal rather than involving the entire digit.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eflexor tendon sheath haematoma\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely given the history of a penetrating injury from a rose thorn, which is more likely to introduce bacteria than cause significant bleeding. Additionally, the progressive worsening over days suggests an infectious rather than traumatic etiology. Patients on apixaban may be more prone to bleeding, but the clinical picture is more consistent with infection.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Efelon\u003C/strong\u003E is a closed-space infection of the pulp of the distal phalanx. It presents with severe throbbing pain, swelling, and erythema limited to the fingertip pulp space. It would not cause tenderness along the entire flexor tendon or the characteristic flexed posture seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003EFlexor tenosynovitis is a surgical emergency requiring prompt treatment with antibiotics and often surgical drainage to prevent tendon necrosis and permanent functional impairment. The infection is commonly caused by penetrating injuries, particularly those involving organic material like plant thorns, which can introduce bacteria directly into the closed tendon sheath space.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Flexor tenosynovitis should be diagnosed using Kanavel\u0027s four cardinal signs: fusiform swelling, finger held in partial flexion, tenderness along the tendon sheath, and pain on passive extension.","Flexor tenosynovitis is a surgical emergency requiring prompt antibiotics and often surgical drainage to prevent tendon necrosis and permanent functional impairment.","Penetrating injuries, especially from organic material like plant thorns, are common causes of flexor tenosynovitis due to bacterial inoculation."],"references":["Evgeniou E, Iyer S. Pyogenic flexor tenosynovitis leading to an amputation. BMJ Case Rep. 2012;2012:bcr2012006778. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22922934/","Hermena S, Tiwari V. Pyogenic Flexor Tenosynovitis. [Updated 2024 Jan 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK576414/","Hyatt BT, Bagg MR. Flexor Tenosynovitis. Orthop Clin North Am. 2017 Apr;48(2):217-227. doi: 10.1016/j.ocl.2016.12.010. PMID: 28336044. Available  from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28336044/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83116"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"891"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83116","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83116"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-26T16:25:49+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-26T16:28:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"891"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100694"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"20","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/20"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4c","name":"Plastic Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"descriptio